seaborn¶

We're going to use a package called seaborn for visualisation. This works 'on top' of the base package matplotlib and offers enhanced functionality and improved graphics. It's possible to produce advanced and slick looking visualisations in seaborn with fairly simple code!

Let's load the package (we'll load matplotlib.pyplot as well, as we will want to alter some of the default settings for plotting

In [3]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

Now, let's set the default figure size (inches), resolution (in 'dots per inch' DPI) and font size

In [4]:
plt.rcParams['figure.figsize'] = [6, 3]
plt.rcParams['figure.dpi'] = 200
plt.rcParams['font.size'] = 10

Neat, we're ready to go!

Scatter plots¶

Scatter plots and line plots are often the first choice when you are plotting one continuous variable against another continuous variable. Let's see an example, plotting how salary has changed with start_date

In [5]:
scatter = sns.scatterplot(data=employees, x='start_date', y='salary')

We see that salary has maintained a fairly uniform spread across the years (this data is clearly synthesised: this wouldn't be true in reality of course). One nice feature of seaborn is that it is easy to 'split' the data in such plots by a third variable. Let's colour the dots by the pension_enrol status of each employee

In [6]:
scatter = sns.scatterplot(data=employees, x='start_date', y='salary', hue='pension_enrol')

Task - 5 mins

  • Change the code for the visualisation above so that we limit employees to just those in the 'Accounting' department [Hint - try .loc[] or .query()].
  • Create a similar visualisation for 'Accounting' employees using the sns.jointplot() function. What extra features does it add to the simple scatterplot, and how do you interpret them?

Solution

In [7]:
# use .query() to select Accounting employees (use .loc[] below)
scatter = sns.scatterplot(
    data=employees.query("department == 'Accounting'"), 
    x='start_date', 
    y='salary', 
    hue='pension_enrol'    
)
In [8]:
# use .loc[] to select Accounting employees (use .query() above)
scatter = sns.jointplot(
    data=employees.loc[employees.department == 'Accounting'], 
    x='start_date', 
    y='salary', 
    hue = 'pension_enrol'
)

The joint plot adds what are called 'densities' to the edges of the plot. These show the distributions of start_date and salary, and are also split by hue= to show any differences due to pension_enrol.

Bar plots and histograms¶

Bar plots are often used to show total counts of levels of a categorical variable, or sometimes the results of an aggregator function applied to a grouping of rows by categorical level. The seaborn package offers a number of functions for categorical visualisation, the simplest being sns.countplot(). Let's use this to plot the numbers of employees in each department

In [9]:
sns.countplot(data=employees, x='department')
Out[9]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='department', ylabel='count'>

Looks promising, but the department labels overlap each other. Let's rotate them

In [10]:
sns.countplot(data=employees, x='department')
# use ; to suppress output of return
plt.xticks(rotation=90);

Task - 2 mins

Now have a go at running this code:

  • What do you think is being plotted on the y-axis?
  • What do the black lines at the tops of the bars show?

[Hint - it may help to look at the docs for sns.barplot()]

In [11]:
sns.barplot(data=employees, x='department', y='salary')
plt.xticks(rotation=90);

Solution

The mean(salary) is being plotted on the y-axis (sns.barplot() defaults to using a mean as its 'estimator'). Each black line shows the 95% 'confidence interval' for the mean: you can interpret this as the likely range for the mean. The longer a particular black line, the more uncertain the mean for that department.

The histogram plays a similar role for a continuous variable as the count plot does for a categorical variable: count the number of values occurring for each level of the variable.

But what does this mean for a continuous variable? Surely, the problem with a continuous variable is that it is possible for each value in the column to be unique or close to unique: a salary of 30,143 is not the same as a salary of 30,144! Well, first the continuous variable is binned prior to plotting: pandas splits the variable up into discrete 'chunks' (or 'bins') and counts the number of values falling in each chunk:

In [12]:
sns.histplot(data=employees, x='salary', binwidth=5000)
Out[12]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='salary', ylabel='Count'>

So, in this plot, the first 'chunk' or bin runs from 20000 to 25000, the second from 25000 to 30000 and so on. The y-axis shows how many salaries lie inside each bin.

Box plots and violin plots¶

Box plots, also known as 'box and whisker' plots are commonly used for data exploration, but are less useful in a presentation to non-analysts, as their interpretation is not straightforward (a histogram or series of histograms would be a better choice in this case). They show the distribution of a continuous variable in an 'at a glance' level, and also show data points likely to be outliers.

See this link for a description of how to interpret boxplots.

In [13]:
sns.boxplot(data=employees, x='department', y='salary')
plt.xticks(rotation=90);

Violin plots might be a better alternative to box plots for an audience who are non-analysts. Within each 'violin' they show the same features as a box plot, but the width of the violin gives an immediate impression of the weight of data lying at that particular y-value. Still, a histogram or series of histograms is arguably a better choice.

In [14]:
sns.violinplot(x='department', y='salary', data=employees)
plt.xticks(rotation=90);

Saving figures¶

Saving figures is easy in seaborn: we first convert our figure to a conventional matplotlib figure using .get_figure(), and then we call the .savefig() method on that figure. We can control the final DPI, and setting argument bbox_inches='tight' lets matplotlib figure out what size of bounding box to use around the plot.

In [15]:
violin = sns.violinplot(x='department', y='salary', data=employees)
plt.xticks(rotation=90);
violin.get_figure().savefig('dept_salary.png', dpi=400, bbox_inches='tight')

You should find a file dept_salary.png in the same folder as your jupyter notebook.

Optional - Faceting¶

The ease of creating faceted plots is one of the main advantages of seaborn over matplotlib. What do we mean by 'faceting'? Well, this corresponds to splitting a single plot into two or more sub-plots, typically based on the value of a categorical variable.

Let's see an example. Imagine we want to plot a series of histograms showing the distribution of salary in each department. We could do this by creating a set of histograms separately, but this is pretty inefficient! How many separate graphs would we need?

In [16]:
employees.department.nunique()
Out[16]:
12

A better approach would be to create a faceted plot: seaborn makes this easy with FacetGrid(). First we create a FacetGrid() object that holds:

  • the DataFrame we want to use
  • the variable(s) we want to facet on (i.e. create a separate sub-plot for each value of this variable). We can use one or two faceting variables, and we can decide how to distribute these over rows and columns of the sub-plots

Let's see the code for our example. Here we want to facet on department, so we set col='department' to tell FacetGrid() to create one long row of sub-plots, each column of the row corresponding to a separate department. We also set col_wrap=3 to tell FacetGrid() to wrap the row in units of 3

In [17]:
grid = sns.FacetGrid(employees, col='department', col_wrap=3)

Neat, it's created the grid three columns wide and four rows tall (remember we asked FacetGrid() to wrap at the third column). But the sub-plots are empty! Next we need to tell seaborn what to plot in each of the facets: we do this with the .map_dataframe() method available on the FacetGrid object we created above.

In our case, we want to create an sns.histplot in each facet, with x='salary. After that we do a little tidying up of the plot: setting axis labels and making the facet titles less wordy.

In [18]:
grid.map_dataframe(sns.histplot, x='salary')
grid.set_axis_labels("Salary", "Count")
grid.set_titles('{col_name}')
Out[18]:
<seaborn.axisgrid.FacetGrid at 0x7fccde90d5b0>

Hopefully this convinces you how useful seaborn can be for visualisation! We have only really scratched the surface: there is much more to discover.
